fields.value: The UNC-Poynter 1996 National Election Study Part I

authorName.value: School of Journalism and Mass Communication, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill

dsDescriptionValue.value: This study corresponds to a study sponsored by the Poynter Institute for Media Studies, St. Petersburg, FL. It is designed to assess the impact of citizen-based journalism in the 1996 national election. The study examined print and television coverage in the 20 U.S. following markets: Charlotte, Norfolk, Portland (OR), Portland (ME), Wichita, Minneapolis, Boston, Rockford, Raleigh, Columbia, Chicago, Des Moines, Richmond, Atlanta, Austin, Birmingham, New Orleans, Houston, Little Rock, and Gra nd Rapids. The study surveyed journalists (by mail) and citizens (by phone) before and after the November election. Additionally, stories printed and broadcast on television were analyzed on their content. Data files are of two kinds: in the journalists and citizens data files the unit of analysis is the individual, in the newspapers and television stations files the unit of analysis is the media.
